Therefore, (ST)(p(x)) = p(x) + xp'(x).

Now, let's interpret (ST)(p(x)) as S(T(p(x))). Applying T to p(x) gives xp(x), then applying S to xp(x) gives p(x) + xp'(x).

Comparing (ST)(p(x)) = p(x) + xp'(x) with S(T(p(x))) = p(x) + xp'(x), we see that these are the same.

Therefore, the correct statement is J: ST = S.
